configWizardOverview.description: Welcome to the Configuration Wizard! This wizard will help you set up MaxScale by guiding you through the process of creating essential objects.
configWizardOverview.intro: Here's what you'll be doing in this wizard:
configWizardOverview.readMoreText: For in-depth details, check our documentation.

steps.description: Represents a database server that clients can connect to via MaxScale, with its status automatically updated by a monitor or manually updatable.
steps.title: Server

steps.description: Monitors the state of a particular kind of cluster and making that state available to the routers of MaxScale.
steps.title: Monitor

steps.description: Customize and control the data that flows through MaxScale. Filters allow you to manipulate and route database traffic to meet your specific requirements.
steps.title: Filter

steps.description: Define the services that MaxScale will provide to your applications. This includes load balancing, read-write splitting, and more.
steps.title: Service

steps.description: Define a port for MaxScale to listen on. It forwards connection requests to the associated service. A listener can be linked to a single service, and multiple listeners can share the same service.
steps.title: Listener

info.clearSelectedQueries: You’re about to delete the {quantity} {targetType}. This action is irreversible. The {quantity} {targetType} will be erased from all logs.
info.columnsLimit: The number of rendered columns is automatically limited to 50 for smoother scrolling and memory management. Use the columns dropdown on the right to toggle visibility. Increasing it can cause the GUI to run out of memory.
info.contact: Thank you for your interest in MariaDB! Please don't hesitate to reach out to us. If you are an existing customer and are looking for help, please use our {url}
info.deleteEtlTask: This would also delete the worksheet used to launch this migration task.
info.disconnectAll: There are open database connections from Workspace. Uncheck the box to keep these connections open.
info.erdTableSupport: ERD is generated based on the definitions of foreign keys. Therefore, only tables using InnoDB storage engines will be displayed since others lack support for foreign keys.
info.etlConfirm: If the destination server already has the same objects they will be overwritten and existing data will be lost.
info.etlDocLinkText: Read more on our documentation for instruction.
info.etlOverviewInfo: MaxScale uses ODBC for extracting and loading from the data source to a server in MaxScale. Make sure you preconfigure the necessary drivers for your data source.

info.fkEngineSupport: Foreign Keys can only be defined for InnoDB tables.
info.identifierAutoCompletion: All identifiers from the active schema will be retrieved automatically upon the initial launch
info.maxStatements: Maximum number of statements to be executed. Increasing it can cause the GUI to run out of memory.
info.migrationScriptInfo: Scripts generated for each table will be executed in parallel. Before migrating, you can make changes to the script.
info.noBackslashEscapes: Disables using the backslash character as an escape character within strings, making it equivalent to an ordinary character.
info.queryIncomplete: Return fewer rows or increase query row limit
info.resTimeDist: Distribution of queries into buckets of response time, similar to {target} in the server.
info.rowLimit: Indicate the number of rows returned from MaxScale. Increasing it can cause MaxScale to run out of memory. Internally we use `sql_select_limit` to limit the maximum number of rows returned
info.showTrendline: The trend line can only be computed for linear axis
info.switchover: Swap the running master with a designated slave
info.tabInsetChar: Pressing Tab in the current editor will insert the tab character. Check the box to change this behavior or while focusing on the editor, press {shortcut}
info.tabMovesFocus: Pressing Tab in the current editor will move focus to the next focusable element. Uncheck the box to change this behavior or while focusing on the editor, press {shortcut}
